WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.130 --> 00:00:03.070
- So what we're talking
about today is isolating

00:00:03.070 --> 00:00:04.833
parts of a muscle.

00:00:06.200 --> 00:00:08.743
Get this topic all the time.

00:00:10.480 --> 00:00:11.970
I can understand where it came from,

00:00:11.970 --> 00:00:16.880
I understand why this is a
thing that people talk about

00:00:16.880 --> 00:00:19.223
and I'm gonna explain
why it's not a thing.

00:00:20.480 --> 00:00:23.220
I'm sure I will upset many individuals

00:00:23.220 --> 00:00:26.250
who have based their life
off of training people

00:00:26.250 --> 00:00:28.750
to isolate parts of the
muscle but you know,

00:00:28.750 --> 00:00:30.610
sorry, it's not a thing.

00:00:30.610 --> 00:00:34.570
So, speaking of upsetting people.

00:00:34.570 --> 00:00:39.570
Last night's post that I made
on Instagram and on Facebook

00:00:39.910 --> 00:00:44.090
was about pull ups and
I'll get to this first

00:00:44.090 --> 00:00:47.040
'cause it actually dove tails
right into this conversation.

00:00:48.180 --> 00:00:49.880
Hey Paul, how you doing?

00:00:49.880 --> 00:00:52.313
Oh, David Fish is on
too, awesome, hey David.

00:00:53.440 --> 00:00:56.680
So, when we talk about pull ups,

00:00:56.680 --> 00:00:59.950
now the research shows
that there's more damage

00:00:59.950 --> 00:01:02.500
in the shoulder joint with pull ups

00:01:02.500 --> 00:01:03.860
than there are with rows.

00:01:03.860 --> 00:01:06.540
Now, keep in mind how research works.

00:01:06.540 --> 00:01:08.980
Also, Zack Salazar had a lot of problems

00:01:08.980 --> 00:01:12.550
with what I said and
he's a really smart dude.

00:01:12.550 --> 00:01:17.163
So I really wanna explain
from his perspective,

00:01:18.260 --> 00:01:23.260
really why I believe this is a problem.

00:01:27.370 --> 00:01:29.330
When a study is done...

00:01:30.240 --> 00:01:32.670
And this is something
about scientific studies

00:01:32.670 --> 00:01:35.910
where sometimes the
press will run away with

00:01:35.910 --> 00:01:38.220
the wrong idea of what a study found

00:01:38.220 --> 00:01:42.460
or they'll look at some
piece of data in the study

00:01:42.460 --> 00:01:44.570
and not really fully
understand the conclusion

00:01:44.570 --> 00:01:46.360
or maybe not wanna
understand the conclusion

00:01:46.360 --> 00:01:48.682
and kind of intentionally misread it.

00:01:48.682 --> 00:01:51.690
(clears throat)

00:01:51.690 --> 00:01:54.250
When a study happens what
they do is they take one group

00:01:54.250 --> 00:01:56.030
and they do one thing,
they take another group

00:01:56.030 --> 00:01:57.490
and they do another thing

00:01:57.490 --> 00:02:00.920
and then they compare the
data, what were the outcomes?

00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:02.600
So they have a group of people

00:02:02.600 --> 00:02:06.887
who have consistently
doing one or the other,

00:02:06.887 --> 00:02:08.960
you know, one thing and
they have another group

00:02:08.960 --> 00:02:09.793
doing the other thing.

00:02:09.793 --> 00:02:12.270
So one group doing bent over rows,

00:02:12.270 --> 00:02:16.400
another group doing pull ups,

00:02:16.400 --> 00:02:20.143
and who had more
inflammation in the joint?

00:02:21.710 --> 00:02:25.850
Often we don't have,
or let's say there's no

00:02:25.850 --> 00:02:28.880
biomechanics specialist or
let's say these individuals

00:02:28.880 --> 00:02:30.710
are unsupervised in the study.

00:02:30.710 --> 00:02:34.450
And they go and often
they do their own thing.

00:02:34.450 --> 00:02:36.753
Well here's the problem
when you do a pull up.

00:02:37.690 --> 00:02:42.690
So, if I were to do a pull up
I would be about right here

00:02:44.024 --> 00:02:45.390
at the top position.

00:02:45.390 --> 00:02:48.090
The problem is when you lock out,

00:02:48.090 --> 00:02:50.610
what happens is you have the opportunity

00:02:50.610 --> 00:02:55.610
to pull your shoulder back
and sometimes people kip.

00:02:55.710 --> 00:02:57.400
So they rock their body forward

00:02:57.400 --> 00:03:01.190
and then use the momentum to bounce off

00:03:01.190 --> 00:03:03.370
kind of the tendons and ligaments in here

00:03:03.370 --> 00:03:04.780
and pull themselves back up,

00:03:04.780 --> 00:03:07.740
and the swing of their body
to get 'em moved forward,

00:03:07.740 --> 00:03:10.960
so they just kind of
pop back into position.

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:13.660
Well, your tendons and
ligaments are not rubber bands.

00:03:14.680 --> 00:03:16.630
They're tissue that you need functioning

00:03:16.630 --> 00:03:17.940
for the rest of your life.

00:03:17.940 --> 00:03:20.930
And also, keep in mind
this joint right here,

00:03:20.930 --> 00:03:23.410
this has the greatest range of motion

00:03:23.410 --> 00:03:25.593
of any joint in the human body.

00:03:26.700 --> 00:03:27.990
So...

00:03:29.200 --> 00:03:30.483
Don't fuck it up.

00:03:33.516 --> 00:03:35.270
You really have a lot of opportunity

00:03:35.270 --> 00:03:37.603
to screw up your shoulder in your life.

00:03:38.760 --> 00:03:41.130
So what I'm trying to
do is encourage people

00:03:41.130 --> 00:03:44.920
to go the lower risk road
and still get the same

00:03:44.920 --> 00:03:46.530
or even greater gains.

00:03:46.530 --> 00:03:48.870
And so when I recommend the bent over row,

00:03:48.870 --> 00:03:50.850
or when somebody says hey
should I throw in pull ups

00:03:50.850 --> 00:03:53.550
and I go, yeah, yeah pull ups are okay.

00:03:53.550 --> 00:03:57.580
But what you wanna make sure is that

00:03:57.580 --> 00:04:00.404
you're doing something that is gonna have

00:04:00.404 --> 00:04:04.313
the greatest reward and the lowest risk.

00:04:04.313 --> 00:04:07.770
So, you can apply the same
thing to investing, right?

00:04:07.770 --> 00:04:09.430
Anything you do in
life, it's like you want

00:04:09.430 --> 00:04:11.100
a very high reward and a very low risk.

00:04:11.100 --> 00:04:12.840
So when you do bent over row,

00:04:12.840 --> 00:04:15.060
especially with variable
resistance with X3,

00:04:15.060 --> 00:04:17.810
you're exhausting
different ranges of motion

00:04:17.810 --> 00:04:20.920
as you go through the
diminishing range and protocol

00:04:20.920 --> 00:04:24.383
and thereby stimulating a great
amount of muscular growth.

00:04:25.600 --> 00:04:29.040
Now, I believe that relatively

00:04:30.680 --> 00:04:34.120
exhausts the questions on this.

00:04:34.120 --> 00:04:36.367
I will go back to questions afterward.

00:04:36.367 --> 00:04:39.030
I saw you guys were
smiling about something,

00:04:39.030 --> 00:04:40.500
did I miss a good question?

00:04:40.500 --> 00:04:41.710
Is there a question?

00:04:41.710 --> 00:04:43.047
No? Okay.
- No, Keith says,

00:04:43.047 --> 00:04:44.400
"Nice work on this topic."

00:04:44.400 --> 00:04:46.363
- Ah, thanks Keith.

00:04:47.560 --> 00:04:49.920
So let's talk about

00:04:51.260 --> 00:04:56.260
the falsehood of fitness of
isolating a part of a muscle.

00:04:57.340 --> 00:05:01.590
So I'm gonna go with an obvious
outrageous example first

00:05:01.590 --> 00:05:03.000
and then I'm gonna talk about

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:07.610
one that almost everybody
seems to be a fan of.

00:05:07.610 --> 00:05:09.540
And then I'm gonna talk
about the clinical research

00:05:09.540 --> 00:05:10.450
on the subject.

00:05:10.450 --> 00:05:15.397
So all the time we hear
people talking about how,

00:05:16.640 --> 00:05:19.960
let's say, one particular
physique star or athlete

00:05:19.960 --> 00:05:24.570
will have an incredibly tall
peak on their bicep, right?

00:05:24.570 --> 00:05:26.290
You'll see him do that and it just like,

00:05:26.290 --> 00:05:28.350
wow they have a really tall peak.

00:05:28.350 --> 00:05:32.068
And then so they're like, hey
I'm gonna right a program...

00:05:32.068 --> 00:05:34.430
See if the people on Instagram,
they can see that, yeah.

00:05:34.430 --> 00:05:36.930
So... (laughs)

00:05:39.165 --> 00:05:42.140
What the question is
somebody has an amazing bicep

00:05:42.140 --> 00:05:45.240
and they say, well, here's my
routine, here's how I did it.

00:05:45.240 --> 00:05:48.930
And people think, okay
so what this guy did

00:05:48.930 --> 00:05:52.040
is how to build a bicep of that shape.

00:05:52.040 --> 00:05:54.990
And so, like Robby Robinson for example,

00:05:54.990 --> 00:05:57.440
was a bodybuilder in the...

00:05:57.440 --> 00:06:00.520
I think like even 60s, 70s and 80s.

00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:01.688
He's still in shape.

00:06:01.688 --> 00:06:05.750
(stammering) Animal, awesome
guy and a cool guy, I met him.

00:06:05.750 --> 00:06:09.350
So what he would talk
about is outward rotation

00:06:09.350 --> 00:06:12.023
while he does bicep work.

00:06:12.870 --> 00:06:14.540
And that's how you build the peak

00:06:14.540 --> 00:06:16.990
'cause it really focuses
on the outer head.

00:06:16.990 --> 00:06:20.330
And having some training (sniffs)

00:06:20.330 --> 00:06:23.230
in physiology and biomechanics,

00:06:23.230 --> 00:06:28.230
your bicep shortens,
like the muscle shortens.

00:06:29.510 --> 00:06:32.500
If that muscle is
shortening and it's doing so

00:06:32.500 --> 00:06:34.400
in a way that your body recognizes

00:06:34.400 --> 00:06:36.610
especially in a multi joint format

00:06:37.560 --> 00:06:40.580
or a stabilization and
single joint format,

00:06:40.580 --> 00:06:45.190
like if you're activating
your biceps via a bicep curl,

00:06:45.190 --> 00:06:46.860
there's all kinds of
stabilization going on,

00:06:46.860 --> 00:06:48.930
you do pick up things with your bicep

00:06:48.930 --> 00:06:52.160
in a single joint manner
and have stabilization

00:06:52.160 --> 00:06:55.610
going through your whole body
to attenuate the forward,

00:06:55.610 --> 00:06:58.570
the sagittal abrupt loading.

00:06:58.570 --> 00:07:02.240
And so there's all kinds of effect there

00:07:02.240 --> 00:07:06.630
and hence the growth hormone
effect that we've seen.

00:07:06.630 --> 00:07:11.630
Okay, so what would happen
was that Robby Robinson,

00:07:13.900 --> 00:07:18.000
he had amazing biceps and
so people wanted to know

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:20.070
what his bicep routine was.

00:07:20.070 --> 00:07:21.940
But here's the problem with that,

00:07:21.940 --> 00:07:26.760
is the shape of a muscle is
like your fingerprint, right?

00:07:26.760 --> 00:07:27.593
Thumbprint.

00:07:29.632 --> 00:07:33.100
It was that way always, so because the guy

00:07:33.100 --> 00:07:35.363
had an amazing shape of bicep,

00:07:37.740 --> 00:07:40.030
whatever he did to make the muscle larger

00:07:40.030 --> 00:07:45.030
made it seem like he did that
so that his bicep would grow

00:07:46.450 --> 00:07:48.250
in a certain shape.

00:07:48.250 --> 00:07:50.360
And the same thing with
Arnold Schwarzenegger.

00:07:50.360 --> 00:07:52.930
How many, probably millions of people,

00:07:52.930 --> 00:07:55.280
follow Arnold Schwarzenegger's program

00:07:55.280 --> 00:07:58.990
because he had a bicep
which looked like an apple.

00:07:58.990 --> 00:08:03.990
Like the tendon was over
here and it was really tall.

00:08:04.580 --> 00:08:07.780
So you would just go, oh whatever he did

00:08:07.780 --> 00:08:08.670
shaped it like that.

00:08:08.670 --> 00:08:11.040
No, no, no, he was born with that.

00:08:11.040 --> 00:08:14.290
And a monument to this is there's

00:08:15.298 --> 00:08:18.610
a lot of people who try
to replicate that shape

00:08:18.610 --> 00:08:20.970
and if they weren't born
with a bicep of that shape,

00:08:20.970 --> 00:08:22.620
they didn't get that.

00:08:22.620 --> 00:08:25.310
Now here's another example:

00:08:25.310 --> 00:08:28.750
when people who have big separation

00:08:28.750 --> 00:08:30.723
from upper to lower pectorals,

00:08:31.690 --> 00:08:33.803
some people do and some people don't,

00:08:34.710 --> 00:08:36.080
they end up writing a program

00:08:36.080 --> 00:08:38.780
about separating upper pectorals.

00:08:38.780 --> 00:08:43.380
Except you can't, that's
not how the muscle fires.

00:08:43.380 --> 00:08:44.813
So here's a great study.

00:08:46.550 --> 00:08:48.910
And very strong evidence.

00:08:48.910 --> 00:08:53.120
Now I've said before,
electromyography is not everything,

00:08:53.120 --> 00:08:54.940
but it does show activity.

00:08:54.940 --> 00:08:57.210
So the idea you can
isolate a part of a muscle,

00:08:57.210 --> 00:08:59.910
this is where electromyography
will be a good test.

00:08:59.910 --> 00:09:04.570
So we would see based
on how much of a part

00:09:04.570 --> 00:09:06.240
of a muscle is contracting.

00:09:06.240 --> 00:09:10.510
So if we can do an exercise
like an incline bench press,

00:09:10.510 --> 00:09:12.433
so you know you're pushing upward,

00:09:13.800 --> 00:09:17.410
or downward for a decline
or for a straight bar

00:09:17.410 --> 00:09:20.510
you're maybe getting a balance of both.

00:09:20.510 --> 00:09:22.900
So they tested these different protocols

00:09:24.690 --> 00:09:28.990
with bench press with 15 young men

00:09:30.080 --> 00:09:35.080
who were doing repetitions
and they put electrodes

00:09:35.140 --> 00:09:36.290
all over the pectorals.

00:09:37.440 --> 00:09:39.887
And what they tried to
do is they did an incline

00:09:39.887 --> 00:09:40.963
and a decline.

00:09:41.970 --> 00:09:45.050
Because what had been said was a decline

00:09:45.050 --> 00:09:46.250
is more for lower pectorals

00:09:46.250 --> 00:09:47.890
and the incline is more
for upper pectorals.

00:09:47.890 --> 00:09:51.360
Now by the way this came out in 1997,

00:09:51.360 --> 00:09:54.400
and this has been a standard thing,

00:09:54.400 --> 00:09:56.960
this is a very famous
study by Stephen Glass

00:09:56.960 --> 00:10:00.120
and Ty Armstrong, two researchers.

00:10:00.120 --> 00:10:01.580
And was published in the

00:10:01.580 --> 00:10:03.940
National Strength Conditioning
Association journal,

00:10:03.940 --> 00:10:06.310
the Journal of Strength
and Conditioning Research.

00:10:06.310 --> 00:10:08.203
So, top world journal.

00:10:09.460 --> 00:10:11.613
Great paper, went through peer review.

00:10:13.434 --> 00:10:15.780
And so what they discovered was

00:10:15.780 --> 00:10:19.260
there was no significant
difference in activity

00:10:21.340 --> 00:10:24.893
between upper and lower pecs
no matter what they did.

00:10:26.140 --> 00:10:29.380
So hence this is a falsehood of fitness,

00:10:29.380 --> 00:10:33.033
and this shit just doesn't
seem to want to go away.

00:10:35.390 --> 00:10:36.970
Like I've tried to tell people this,

00:10:36.970 --> 00:10:39.070
you can't isolate a part of a muscle.

00:10:39.070 --> 00:10:42.200
And I think people just
don't like that answer.

00:10:42.200 --> 00:10:45.560
And so we're all victims at
times of confirmation bias.

00:10:45.560 --> 00:10:49.090
Just look at how people
research political issues.

00:10:49.090 --> 00:10:51.460
They search for something
that will give them

00:10:51.460 --> 00:10:54.993
the answer they want,
not the answer that is.

00:10:56.870 --> 00:11:00.510
When somebody says I wanna
grow my upper pectorals,

00:11:00.510 --> 00:11:03.320
there are trainers out
there who truly believe

00:11:03.320 --> 00:11:05.630
they're helping people
develop their upper pectorals.

00:11:05.630 --> 00:11:08.950
And so here's one thing to point out,

00:11:08.950 --> 00:11:13.950
if I push down and I look at
what my pectoral looks like,

00:11:15.460 --> 00:11:17.660
it looks thicker on the bottom.

00:11:17.660 --> 00:11:19.960
And if I push up like this,

00:11:19.960 --> 00:11:23.140
it looks like my pectoral
is thicker at the top.

00:11:23.140 --> 00:11:27.610
So it looks like it's more
contracted, but it isn't.

00:11:27.610 --> 00:11:29.000
Like these things shorten.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:31.630
And one of the most ludicrous
things I've seen recently

00:11:31.630 --> 00:11:34.980
is building the inner pectoral,

00:11:34.980 --> 00:11:39.160
which is, you know, not a thing.

00:11:39.160 --> 00:11:42.630
I mean, that's not even muscle,
that's connective tissue.

00:11:42.630 --> 00:11:44.970
Like it's where the muscle
comes into the sternum,

00:11:44.970 --> 00:11:47.250
so (chuckles) that's not a thing.

00:11:47.250 --> 00:11:49.630
Now if you do make your pectorals bigger,

00:11:49.630 --> 00:11:52.240
you will have a thicker inner chest.

00:11:52.240 --> 00:11:55.350
But you'll have a thicker
chest and whatever shape,

00:11:55.350 --> 00:11:57.310
what you were born with, like a thumbprint

00:11:57.310 --> 00:11:58.570
is how it's gonna look.

00:11:58.570 --> 00:12:02.497
Now some people have no idea
what the shape of a muscle is.

00:12:02.497 --> 00:12:04.740
And if they're carrying
around a significant

00:12:04.740 --> 00:12:06.780
amount of body fat and
they have an underdeveloped

00:12:06.780 --> 00:12:08.690
muscle under there, so you know,

00:12:08.690 --> 00:12:10.430
what are you gonna look like
when you're totally lean?

00:12:10.430 --> 00:12:12.590
Well, there's only one way to find out

00:12:12.590 --> 00:12:14.263
and that's get totally lean.

00:12:16.890 --> 00:12:21.150
Fantastic study again,
Glass and Armstrong, 1997

00:12:21.150 --> 00:12:24.730
Journal of Strength and
Conditioning Research.

00:12:24.730 --> 00:12:29.730
I said I would only bore
you guys with one reference,

00:12:29.740 --> 00:12:34.490
one piece of academic research
per one of these videos

00:12:34.490 --> 00:12:35.733
and I did that.

00:12:36.800 --> 00:12:39.353
Let's open it up for questions.

